Put place-holder logic in place for <authentication> and <encryption>. We now have placeholders ready, although <encryption> has a base
implementation. When running the example federate currently it will fail
due to the RTI not yet properly handling the change from sync/async
messages to CallType driven messages (Data, Control & Notification).

Refactor the structure of the ConnectionConfiguration to better encapsulate the separation of JVM/TCP/Multicast as _transports_, not the whole connection. There is now a generic ConnectionConfiguration class. From that class
you can fetch the TransportConfiguration and the ProtocolStack.

A bit of juggling necessary because a transport _is_ a protocol (so that
it can be insertered into the protocol stack as the last element).
Commences cut-over to XML configuration. Refactors a number of key components WIP - Still require a way to pass configuration information to Protocols

Introduce the WIP base structure of an XML configuration for the RID This moves the RID configuration from a properties file to an XML one.
With the recent changes there has been the introduction of a log more
nested configuration information. This doesn't translate well to the
properties format and it can be confusing. As such, I'm introducing an
XML configuration file. The configuration code is a little more...
effort, but the actual configuration file itself is pretty simple.

This commit has the base infrastructure for most of it and cuts the RTI
RID parser over to use the XML version. Tasks to complete:

  - Move LRC and Forwarder objects over to this format
  - Remove the old properties based configuration classes
  - Move the current XML files out of the .xml sub-package
  - Add support for command-line args overrides
  - Add support for RTIambassador::connect() overrides

Overhaul the structure of the header to be more efficient and streamlined. This is a partial commit of WIP. It overhauls the structure of the
header to enable more efficient processing and a better separation of
both Encryption/Authentication, and to add a new message call type
called a "Notification". This replaces the Async control messages of the
past, which were also confusing as they implied a certain value of
"isFromRti" in the Portico message itself. Now we have:

  - Data Messages: As they were
  - Control Request: Between single RTI and Federate
  - Control Response: Response to a Control Request
  - Notification: Unsolicited message sent from the RTI

Further updates to come will split Authentication and Encryption
(currently the PKI and Symmetric packages do not do this well) and will
move the RIT to an XML format.

RtiInbox federation firewall no longer blocks messages from the RTI - In #276 we added a clause to the RtiInbox that rejected incoming
  messages if they came from a federate that was not an execution
  member. This had the unintended consequence of blocking messages from
  the RTI itself (E.g. mom interactions).
- Updated the clause to also accept messages from the RTI

Fixes C++ datatype retrieval to work with new XmlRenderer - Updated C++ DatatypeRetrieval xpath queries to conform to the
  spec-compliant XmlRenderer output on the java side. The previous
  version of XMLRenderer used to output an xml document from either an
  older version of the spec, or an unofficial format (values were in
  attributes rather than in nested child elements).
- ObjectModel.setObjectRoot() now adds and caches the privilegeToDelete
  attribute if the new donor ocroot does not contain it. This was to fix
  an issue whereby createFederationExecution() is called with multiple
  modules, the first of which does not contain
  HLAobjectRoot.privilegeToDelete. In this case, the attribute was being
  added by the second module, however it wasn't being cached to the
  ObjectModel.privilegeToDelete() member, and thus causing NPEs further
  down the chain.

Refactored protocol framework to support direct message passing between protocols. This refactor is needed to support protocols that must take additional,
independent actions by passing more than one message per message
received, or passing messages up/down the stack between themselves.

Add a basic connection status property to the Connection class. This is for external management by the host component. When it believes

Various protocols will also watch, use or update this status as needed.

Support encryption via pre-shared key stored in RID file. This is temporary. It is a place-holder while we move to a proper
key-exchange protocol where federates use public key crypto during
connection and exchange a session key that is then used at runtime.

Next steps are to get the basics of asym working and then implement
the exchange protocol.

MOM support for service invocation information and exceptions #237 - Added framework for Service Invocation reporting

Adds new centralized MomManager and initial support for MOM interactions This commit contains work for Portico tickets #230 and #238

Centralized MomManager (#230)
=============================

A MomManager for the new centralized RTI has been put in place. The instance
lives within the RTI's Federation class and creates a HLAFederation that
mirrors it. As federates join, new HLAFederate objects are added to the
Federation's object Repository, so that ordinary federates can discover them.

The RTI handler code for RequestObjectUpdate has been modified to route
requests for any HLAFederation or HLAFederate objects to the MomManager which
will generate an appropriate ReflectAttributeValues message for them
(ordinarily these requests would be forwarded to the federate that owns the
objects).

Code to serialize the values of all previously supported HLAFederation and
HLAFederate attributes has been ported over. In some cases the encoding needed
to be fixed to be standard compliant (Handles and Time Values are actually
HLAvariableArrays of HLAbyte not just a plain HLAinteger64BE etc.

I've also added metric tracking for the following Federate attributes:

- HLAreflectionsReceived
- HLAupdatesSent
- HLAinteractionsReceived
- HLAinteractionsSent
- HLAobjectInstancesThatCanBeDeleted
- HLAobjectInstancesUpdated
- HLAobjectInstancesReflected
- HLAobjectInstancesDeleted
- HLAobjectInstancesRemoved
- HLAobjectInstancesRegistered
- HLAobjectInstancesDiscovered

All of these metrics are contained in the class FederateMetrics, which is
saved against the RTI Federate object. While these weren't part of the original
request, they are essential for the subsequent MOM Request/Report interactions
that need to be implemented, so it felt like an appropriate time to add them.

The Mom object has been significantly reworked to support the nested
nature of MOM interactions, and to allow for a cross-version name
lookup. Both object and interactions have been updated to the new system
and unit tests have been updated accordingly.

Everything looks to be working ok using the test federate that Tim provided.

MOM Support for request/report synchronization point status (#238)
==================================================================
This task involved creating a framework for the processing of MOM
request interactions. All SendInteraction message that the RTI hears
about are forwarded to the MomSendInteractionHandler which inspects the
handle of the interaction and passes it onto a relevant processor.

Decoding of request parameter values is taken care of by the framework.
The handler then compiles response parameters, and then asks the
framework to encode them and send the response.

If an exception is raised during the processing of the request (e.g.
missing parameters, invalid parameters) the processor raises a
MomException which the framework reports back to the Federate through
the HLAreportMOMexception interaction.

Using this framework I've implemented the following request/response
interaction pairs

- HLArequestSynchronizationPoints/HLAreportSynchronizationPoints
- HLArequestSynchronizationPointStatus/HLAreportSynchronizationPointStatus

Split OCInstance/ACInstance into RTI/LRC variants. Previously we had single classes representing object and attribute
instances. Now that we have a separate LRC and RTI, they need to track
different things against each object/attriute. The differences are
substantial enough that a single OCInstance/ACInstance type is no longer
suitable.

This commit refactors them out into variants for the RTI and LRC:

  - (RTI) ROCInstance/RACInstance
  - (LRC) LOCInstance/LACInstance

PORT-256 Defer linking until all FOM modules have been parsed and merged (#261) * PORT-256 Defer linking until all FOM modules have been parsed and merged

- When we initially developed the datatype parsing system, we worked under
  the assumption that all FOM modules were standalone in their own right -
  e.g. the datatypes has declarations for all datatypes that are referenced
  in the module.
- However in the modular RPR FOM this is not the case. Datatypes,
  attributes and parameters can all reference datatypes that are
  declared soley in other FOM modules.
- As such all the DatatypePlaceholder is now placed for all datatype
  links at parse time. Linking is deferred until all FOM modules have
  been parsed and merged, and the standard MIM has been inserted.
- Updated parsing unit tests to perform the delayed linking process.

(MAJOR REFACTOR) Move from fully distributed to a central RTI process. This is part of major ongoing work to support #219. We are moving to a
central RTI process where the administrative tasks are all completed
inside the RTI, but high-volume messages like data exchanges are still
routed over efficient, multicast networks.

We are also adding in more robust network-bridging unicast support that
will replace the WAN Forwarder and support filtering of messages based
on rules configurable inside the RID.

This commit is the first major step. It adds a temporary portico2 folder
that replicates a lot of existing structure and brings into place a
separate RTI, LRC and Forwarder component that serve each of the major
subsystems. It currently only supports 1516e and still have many broken
parts, however the infrastructure and core services are present and it
is robust enough to support further development by more than one person.

This commit represents a number of previous WIP changes squashed into
one bulk of work. Due to the above, the individual changes are extremely
broad and too numerious to list individually. Rather, this consolidated
commit just marks the state from which a more managed process should be
undertaken.

Remove the "Dtx" RTIamb extension for 1516e and put in a general version Building on the old "JLC" apporach from the past, I have added an
"extensions" package to the standard 1516e Java interfaces. This
contains a single RTIambassadorEx interface that extends the default
RTIambassador and adds our custom methods.

This change is mirrored inside the implementation code and I have
flicked the default Rti1516eAmbassador to abstract to ensure that we
only ever pass the extended version. So now:

  hla.rti1516e.RTIambassador >> org.portico.impl.hla1516e.Rti1516eAmbassador (abstract)
  hla.rti1516e.extensions.RTIambassadorEx >>  org.port....Rti1516eAmbassadorEx (concrete)

Remove the use of ServiceRegistry in the standard/header 1516e classes. The use of ServiceRegistry in Java 9 is now hard limited to only a
particular set of Java IO/Image types. The 1516e standard headers used
it for a generic lookup mechanism, which frankly was a bit of a smell
(take one look at the package the classes were in and you know they were
not meant for this purpose).

Portico-specific implementations. Fine because it'll all be hidden to
the user if they change RTIs.

Change the way handlers are loaded to remove dynamic classpath lookup. Previously, handlers were loaded by searching certain parts of the classpath
for the @MessageHandler annotation. The "certain parts" bit is what caused
most of the problem. We couldn't search the full classpath, because in many
cases it is enormous. As such, we tried to limit the search locations to
the location of portico.jar (to get the main plugins that make up the RTI)
and a dedicated "plugins" folder.

This is all fine as long as you can find portico.jar. The failure to find
the jar is often perfectly valid (expanded code on classpath, Eclipse builds
etc...). As such, not finding it isn't an error and if the environment is
properly configured, the core plugins will be found via a dedicated plugin
folder. This is already sounding complicated. To make it worse, when lookup
failed you wouldn't get an error (because it might be valid), instead you'd
get a cryptic "null returned for sink" or some such error caused by there
being no handler to deal with a given message because it was never found.

Anyway, long story short - nobody was using the plugins mechanism, and
frankly, if anyone did they'd have other issues so I am just taking it away.
In its place I've put in a MessageRegistry class that just does the work of
manually registering the core handlers. Simple, in fact it is down right
"not clever" in most ways... which means it works.

fin.

Enable bundling on WAN connections for high throughput performance This commit adds proper bundling support to the LocalGateway so that
messages sent over the WAN can be grouped togethe to make more efficient
use of network resources. Testing locally has shown that with bundling
enabled, throughput tests are able to ready ~80% of the local multicast
performance with two federates.

The previously seen memory exhaustion issues have also started to be
controlled. Bundling means fewer messages are sent, and although they
are larger, the overall send time vice individual messages is much
smaller. As such, fewer messages end up queued and the router appears to
reach a steady state. To provide some extra room, the WAN Router startup
scripts increase the heap memory slightly, although this did not seem to
be fully necessary and is a safety precaution only.

Fix bug that truncates large attribute updates at 989 bytes. The `ObjectInput.read()` call being used to fetch attribute data from
the incoming buffer was only reading the first 989 bytes. We had
pre-allocated a buffer with the correct size, so this resulted in the
appearance of truncation after this position. Changing the call to
`readFully()` ensured that the full amount of data available was being
read.

Change has been made for both the UpdateAttributes and SendInteraction
message classes. Unit tests for sizes of 1MB confirm the behaviour.

Fix #54 - I believe the cause of the NPE was that the local federate was resigning, which was stripping the LRC off the message receiver, but that a separate thread was still processing a message, and when it got to hand off to the LRC, found that it was null. I've put both the receive and lifecycle methods into "synchronized" so they can't be run parallel to one another now which should clear it up. Haven't been able to reproduce the problem since, but will keep an eye out.

Changed the 1516e RTIamb so that it no longer logs a message about every exception at the ERROR level. Messages are now logged at debug. Just because there is an exception doesn't mean there is an error. There are many sitautions where we may expect an exception (such as trying to destroy a federation that is still in use when the local federate shuts down). Exposing this as an error message means it is printed in the console for every user, all the time. Dropped the level to DEBUG so that it is still logged, but you have to want to see more information to get it.

Bumped the "MOM not supported in 1516e" warning message down to info. It was just too nagging to have it pop up on every. single. execution. It's a message for the developer, and I am making every *user* look at it. Poor UX, Tim. Poor UX. Now falls below the default WARN level, but can be seen easily by setting
the level to INFO or lower.
Updated the logging configurator so that the log file does not roll over. It will now be overwritten each time you do a simulation run.

Working #120: Added proper clone() support to UpdateAttributes. And by "proper", I mean enough to support the JVM. It still isn't a true clone in the sense that all the values are not copied. But as most attributes of message classes are read-only on the incoming handlers, it is safe to only have a shallow clone. Awesome.

Fix #63. Turns out I was overwriting the JGroups configuration by just setting up my own Executor, with its own arbitrary settings, in code. This was falling back to the default rejection handler of Abort, which was causing the exceptions. Fixed now so that the executor will use the jgroups configured executor and the setting of "Run" will flow through.
Fix #118 Calling disconnect() now properly shuts the immediate callback dispatcher down if it is running. Also made the dispatcher thread a daemon so that it will never hold a process open by itself.

Enable clusters of federates to communicate across a WAN At each site, a single federate must have the WAN mode turned on inside
their RID file. When enabled, all messages received on the local JGroups
channel (which includes the messages sent by the local federate itself)
will be forwarded to a central messages router where they will be sent
out to all other connected clients.

Messages received from the router will be put on the local JGroups
channel where they are picked up and processed by the locally attached
federates.

	codebase/system/ant-optional/cpptask.jar
Updated the BitHelpers to use stdint types. Hopefully will clear up some win/lin issues. Only tested in Mac OS X at the moment. Looking for clarification on Windows.
Bringing in work on maintenance branch for pull request #35 from lumixen. Small changes needed to swap in stdint types. Merge remote-tracking branch 'lumixen/maintenance-2.0.x' into maintenance-2.0.x
(continued from previous commit). Updating the version of Java we target to 7u45
(continued from previous commit). Updating the version of Java we target to 7u45
Moving the Java version we target for packaging along to 7u45

Updated build files that remove jdk.home/jdk.default pairs used in compiling (linking to the JDK) and packaging (packaging a JRE) in favour of just a single jdk.home setting per platform. Removed the use of tasks marked as deprecated in cpptask.

IEEE1516E data structs updated: - Fixed several encoding\decoding bugs related to the vc10 compiler. - Fixed getting a wrong pointer to the data in some structures. - Replaced 'long' by 'long long' for processing 64 bit values. Long is 4-bytes length on MS platforms.
Fixed getting a wrong address pointer while encoding\decoding C++ HLAopaqueData && HLAvariableArray structs.
Fixed getting a wrong address pointer while encoding and decoding C++ HLAfixedArray struct.
Merge remote-tracking branch 'origin/maintenance-2.0.x'
Merge pull request #34 from lumixen/maintenance-2.0.x Fixed constant "Insufficient data .." exception while decoding ieee1516e...
Fixed constant "Insufficient data .." exception while decoding ieee1516e strings caused of getting wrong pointer to the data array in the decode method.
Merge pull request #31 from calytrix/port139-java6support Added Java 6 compatible libraries
[PORT-139] Updated both the custom-compiled versions of cpptask and jgroups with versions that were compiled with v1.6 compatibility.
[PORT-139] Updated both the custom-compiled versions of cpptask and jgroups with versions that were compiled with v1.6 compatibility.
Minor style and convention updates to JPL patch. All good and ready for merge into the maintenance branch so it rolls into the next point update.
Patch to allow key variables to be passed to an existing running JVM - probably just occurs within Matlab. The same patch should probably be done for HLA 1.3 as well
Small copy update. Because there wasn't enough sass in the previous one.
Updated the L&F a little bit. Pretty much ready to start filling out now.

First cut at a new style for the website. Just placeholder and L&F stuff at the moment. A lot of doco to port and write. Will look to package the whole website as doco with each release. Consistent experience on and offline that way.
Renaming the patches file to include the revision number it came off.
Adding in a patch file that contains the custom Ant hacks (current as of April 14, 2013).

Updated ant jar file with a fix for a problem with resolving prefixed dependencies that have the name of the prefix as another part of their dependency name. E.g. the dependency is "common.retail.assemble" and the project has an imported prefix of "retail". The depedency becomes "retail.common.retail.assemble" which needs to have retail stripped from the front. Only problem is that "retail." was being removed from the WHOLE string, not just the front. Fixed now.

Fixed up the Windows NSIS installer generator. Somehow, due to solar wind or something, I forgot to uncomment the lines that actually included Portico in the installer (I commented them out originally to do a little testing). All better now, except for my head. It still hurts from making rapid movement towards the desk followed by a sudden stop.
Fixing some small typos in the various build files to account for changes over the past few weeks (property and file name changes but not updated everywhere - that sort of thing).

Updated the windows installers to include version information in their details panels and verified a fix for the problems encountered running the C++ ieee1516e example federates (was fixed in master but I hadn't merged over to get those updates yet). Everything looks good and ready for production.
Merge remote-tracking branch 'origin/master' into windowsInstallers
Fixed the Windows installers so that we now have actual NSIS installers rather than just zip files. Also fixed a problem with the 64-bit zip files that were omitting the actual core RTI jar file!

commit_message: PORT-137 Fixed the same "release builds not including C++" problem that was being experienced on Linux.
PORT-137 Updated the linux install so that calling ./ant release actually generated C++ artefacts. Now all works perfectly happily with Ubuntu 12.04LTS 64-bit.

PORT-137 Updated the linux example federate helper scripts and fixed a bug that was preventing users of the C++ interface from creating a federation without specifying a time type (there is an overload where you don't specify any type and just take the default - which was failing due to a recent change). Linux 64-bit is now happy!

PORT-137 Support now added for compiling up the C++ 1516e interface. This build generates a few more warnings than the HLA v1.3 build. These will need to be seen to, but for now we'll live with them. Note that without a C++ 1516e test suite I can't test this build properly yet. The example federate compile scripts are also broken and unfortunately I'm out of time tonight.

PORT-137 Reintroduced the Linux C++ HLA v1.3 library generation. This currently only supports 64-bit (that's the only VM I have at the moment) but seems to compile everything up just fine (ignoring a bunch of warnings) and runs the full C++ test suite fine. Time to move on to IEEE-1516e 64-bit compiling and then on to 32-bit!
Merge pull request #29 from calytrix/master Portico v2.0.0 Public Release

PORT-122: Added support for enable/disable callbacks. When enabled, a block is put on tick processing. Added an implementation of a support service message (getKnownObjectClassHandle()) as its absence was breaking the test. Not sure why it was left unimplemented as it was about 4s work, but it's done now.

PORT-109 Reduced the log level of all standard HLA service call notifications to trace from debug and info. Have not touched the logging calls for the rest of the framework (such as initial loading and initialization events).

PORT-112 Updated the Rti1516eAmbassador to throw a different exception when given a non-standard time type (CouldNotCreateLogicalTimeFactory). Added tests to the Java ieee1516e test suite to verify this.
PORT-112 Added a check to ensure that the time implementation name provided (where provided) is one of the standard types. If it is not, an RTIinternalError will be thrown.

PORT-83 Have now fought tooth and nail with C++ string and macro combinations and believe I have the version flowing through from the build and into Portico C++ properly. Final testing needed on windows to ensure I didn't break anything.

PORT-133: Refactored the Java tests for 1516/e from the names hla1516e to ieee1516e (and the same for plain 1516). Fixed up the build so that the tests are actually called under the new name. No need for any C++ change as there is no C++ 1516/e test suite yet.
No idea why the Eclipse C++ project file changed. A pox on it.

PORT-90 #comment Updated the C++ Eclipse project settings to be clearner and more sane. Have build configurations that happily work on the Mac now but need to roll these out to Windows and Linux. Unfortunately it doesn't look like I can embed the code templates in the project, so the main thrust for this issue has come to naught. I remain scarred by the experience however.
PORT-2: Patch applied to set so that first() and last() now return -1 when the indexes are not valid rather than throwing an exception as before (which is against the standard).
PORT-135: Pulled out the old system information piece from Portico and put in a main class so that system details are printed to the console when java -jar portico.jar is invoked.
Fixing up header comments on all the tests for HLA-Evolved encoding helpers written by @michaelrfraser BECAUSE HE KILLED THE FORMATTING. The Shame.
PORT-86: Added README files to each of the example federates and ensured that windows, linux and mac starter scripts are present.
PORT-86: Added the standard RID files to each of the examples directory just to make things easier for people when running them and wanting to turn logging up.
PORT-134: Attempting to get the stupid linux installer task working in the bamboo build system. Working on my local Ubuntu dev VM. Will hopefully find its JRE now.
PORT-134: Added the proper JDK localization stuff to the linux installer and fixed the tar command so that it is formatted properly for the linux version of tar rather than the Mac OS X version
PORT-134: Fixing a typo in the main build file that was causing the linux installer build file to not be imported.
PORT-134 Adding a basic linux installer profile so that the nightly build will not barf about being unable to find its build artefact.
Merge pull request #28 from calytrix/port-134-bamboo-builds PORT-134 Continuous Integration Updates
PORT-134 Properly disabling the HLA v1.3 tests on Windows now. Previouly disabled them only for release builds.
PORT-134 #comment Making sure the javadoc task only runs on a release build.
Merge pull request #27 from timpokorny/port134-portico-bamboo PORT-134: Updated the Windows C++ builds to tie into release generation
PORT-134: Updated the Windows C++ builds to tie into the release generation, but disabled them temporarily while there are still remaining crashing issues with CppUnit to sort out.
Merge pull request #26 from timpokorny/port134-portico-bamboo PORT-134 Updated packaging JRE version to 1.7.0_17
PORT-134: Updated the Java build version to 1.7.0_17.
Merge pull request #25 from timpokorny/port134-portico-bamboo PORT-134 Continues Integration Build
PORT-134: Removed the ftp stuff from the deployment script. We're not going to use that so we should get rid of it.
PORT-134: Small update to include the build number in the uploaded nightly resources.
PORT-134: Fixed a typo that was looking for the directory to upload from in the wrong location
PORT-134: Added an scp-based deploy task to the build to support automatic deployment of nightly builds.
PORT-134: Updating the build number to 2.0.0 (removed -dev) as the next public build will be final. Using this to test Bamboo plan branches.
PORT-134: Fixing the test that was failing on purpose.
PORT-134: Committing failing test to validate Bamboo setup.
PORT-134: Distribution now include build numbers both in the jar file and stamped on the DLLs
PORT-134: Updated CppTask with support for resource file compiling.

PORT-134: Update the build so that it takes the JDK version from a separate build.properties file. Also moved the version information into this file so that all overrides are stored in the same place.

PORT-134: Updated the installers to remove "dist.*" paths and replace them with "sandbox.*" ones (makes things more consistent and true to what they actually are). Updated the jar task so that the build.versions file is included inside it and so the version is pulled from that file.
Removing the DAMN ECLIPSE CDT PROJECT settings for now. Need to fix them up as something is absolutely screwy, but will start from scratch to do this. Stupid CDT.
Merge pull request #24 from timpokorny/master Updated dist.sandbox.dir to sandbox.dir
Updated the build to rename "dist.sandbox.dir" to "sandbox.dir" as per my delicate sensibilities.
Merge pull request #23 from timpokorny/port100-jvm-packaging PORT-100: Packaging (32 and 64-bit)

PORT-100: Updated the packaging on Windows to produce two separate zip files (one for 32 and 64 bit). Updated and tested the example federates. Also fixed a stupid, idiotic, obvious bug in the common.h headers for HLA13 and IEEE1516e. On Windows, they were ALWAYS setting the system up for x86 regardless of whether the system was 32 or 64-bit as the preprocessor definition it was looking for to signal that we are on Windows 32-bit is always present on Windows 64-bit as well. Had to flip the test so that we test for 64-bit support first and then fall back to 32-bit (rather than the other way around). Fixed now. Embarrassment.
PORT-100: Updated the build so that it will now more readily support 32/64-bit separate builds. Works on the Mac, need to test and fix on Windows.
Merge pull request #22 from timpokorny/port3-vc8support PORT-3 VC8 builds
PORT-3: Updated build now works happily on Mac OS X
Merge of Windows changes into Mac OSX dev build
Updated a few simple properties in the JGroups UDP configuration.
PORT-3: Updated the Eclipse project to use the active build configuration for the indexer (hopefully it sticks this time!)
PORT-3: Ported to IEEE1516e on Windows now. Time to address the platform specific installers.

PORT-3: Updated the windows build to make use of the new build profiles facility. This allows someone to specify which of the C++ builds to run via a special comma-separated system property. Rather than call big long targets, they can just list off which compilers, architectures and build types they want and the build will figure the rest out. Currently only enabled on the HLA v1.3 build.

PORT-3: Updates to the build to happily generate distributions that cover vc8, vc9 and vc10 (32/64 bit, debug and release). This included some cpptask updates and some small code fixes to ensure that the interface compiled up happily with VC8 (eww).
Merge pull request #21 from timpokorny/port125-64bitLibraries PORT-125: 64-bit library naming
PORT-125: Updated the name of the library produced to conform to the correct conventions.
PORT-125: Updated the Eclipse C-project settings to include specific references to the JVM and CppUnit libraries and to always use the active configuration for indexing.
Merge pull request #20 from timpokorny/port72-buildprocess PORT-72 Build Process Updates
Updates to Portico so that stdint.h works across all compiler versions across Windows.
PORT-128: Same F****** PROBLEM WITH TRANSPORT HANDLES AS PREVIOUS COMMIT

PORT-128: The ordering handles were not being converted properly. The specification defines then as an enumeration and then gives them a value (1 and 2), but at the same time provides no way to access that value!! WHAT THE F***!? Anyway, I hacked in a little conversion method to get around that idiotic problem.

PORT-128: Filling out the SupplementalInformation which like the sent and received ordering was also causing crashing passing across the C++ boundary. Need to do it here so I can validate the sent/received ordering fix.

PORT-128: Added in defaults for the sent and received ordering values, as well as the transport handles. These try to get as close as I can while still guessing based on the situation (for example, the sent and received ordering is RELIABLE if the message is delivered TSO) but I have not put in a full implementation. The defaults have been added to all overloads of the following methods:  * reflectAttributeValues()
 * receiveInteraction()
 * removeObjectInstance()

It's too much of a stretch to calculate the proper values inside the
callback handler (performance hit as the RTI has to reach back into its
stores to do more processing). When done properly, these should be done
by the generic handlers further back in the chain, but there is a bit of
work to do there so I'm just choosing sensisble defaults for now given
that the primary target audience of Portico is the training domain where
these values are ignored anyway (in fact, I'm trying to think of ANY
domain where these values are used).

PORT-124: When an exception occurs in Java, a call is made to an Exception handling class. The call passes the exception name and a reason for the exception. This name is then compared to a list of known names, and when a match is found, the appropriate exception is thrown. As it's pretty boilerplat, the code to throw the exception is in a macro, but the macro was faulty and was causing the comparisons to not be made against the actual exception name, but rather against the name of the parameter variable used in the macro. Fixed now. Head appropriately planted on the desk.

there, but not in the namespace *facepalm*

PORT-72: Fixed the unit-test crashing for the C++ HLA13 test suite. I reordered the way the C++ side was structing the classpath when invoking the JVM. Previously, it used the system classpath first, then put in RTI_HOME/lib/portico.jar. This was a problem because the build is setting a fake RTI_HOME (as the C++ side won't start without the variable being set) but then going on to set the classpath up correctly. So the RTI_HOME/lib/portico.jar file was getting in ahead of the actual portico jar file, and for some reason, my automated, annotations based message handler loading thing was picking only the first jar file entry to scan, seeing there wasn't anything (as the file didn't exist) and giving up. Changing this around so that the existing classpath is put first has fixed this. One line! It's always one line! A bit brittle, and yet another sign that I should just rid myself of the auto-message handler loading stuff and have some explicit code somewhere to register the handlers, but that'll have to wait for now. Fixed and working on Mac and Win32.
